{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GPG4vq5nRqyYKEma13Bp1H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good picture of the lodash versions. Let me figure out what's pulling in lodash in the jest yarn.lock and check the version resolution in webpack too. The jest yarn.lock appears to be a Yarn v2/berry format (it uses `lodash@npm:...`). \n\nThe jest yarn.lock resolves all lodash versions (^4.15.0, ^4.17.15, ^4.17.19, ^4.17.20, ^4.17.21, ^4.17.4, ~4.17.15) to **4.17.21** - which is the patched version.\n\n\nThe webpack yarn.lock does the same, resolving lodash (^4.17.15, ^4.17.19, ^4.17.21, ^4.17.4, ^4.7.0) to **4.17.21**. Now I need to trace which packages in the jest workspace are actually pulling in lodash - I noticed `^4.17.19` at line 307 from `@babel/core`. Let me check the lodash package itself and see what version it declares.\n\nLooking at the lodash package.json, it's at version 4.17.20 with lodash 4.17.14 as a devDependency, which means the package itself is vulnerable since 4.17.20 is less than 4.17.21. Now I'm scanning through the jest yarn.lock to find which packages declare lodash as a dependency - I can see `^4.17.19` appearing at multiple locations including as part of @babel/core's dependencies.\n\nI'm also noticing the jest examples directory has lodash `^4.17.19` in its package.json. So across the three workspaces, I have lodash 4.17.20 (vulnerable) in the lodash package itself, webpack resolving to 4.17.21 (patched), and jest's examples pinned to `^4.17.19`. Let me trace through the jest monorepo more systematically to see which specific packages depend on lodash.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":835,"cache_read_input_tokens":38176,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":835},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_g